4 R UNTIME SYSTEMS DETAILS 4.1 Cython 0.19.1 <http://cython.org/> Cython is a compiler for a superset of the Python language.

4.2 Falcon 0.05 <https://github.com/rjpower/falcon> Falcon is a Python extension module that hacks into a CPython interpreter and changes the execution loop, implementing several optimizations (for instance, using a register-based VM instead of a stack-based one) that the Falcon authors think should be used in the upstream CPython interpreter too.
4.3 Numba <http://numba.pydata.org/> As its website states: Numba is an optimizing compiler for Python; it uses the LLVM compiler infrastructure to compile Python syntax to machine code.
4.4 Nuitka 0.4.4 <http://www.nuitka.net/> Nuitka translates Python (2.6+) into a C++ program that then useslibpython to execute in the same way as CPython does, in a very compatible way.
4.5 PyPy 2.1 <http://pypy.org/> PyPy is a Python language interpreter with a Just-In-Time compiler (and many other features!).

1.Introduction The First Workshop on Sustainable Software for Science: Pra ctice and Experiences (WSSSPE1, http://wssspe.researchcomputing.org.uk/WSSSPE1) was h eld on Sunday, 17 November 2013, in conjunction with the 2013 International Conference for Hig h Performance Computing, Networking, Storage and Analysis (SC13, http://sc13.supercomputing.

Additionally, a minisymposium at the 2014 Society for Industrial and Applied Mathematics (SIAM) Annual Meeting on ‚ÄúReliable Com putational Science‚Äù (SIAM AN14, http://meetings.siam.org) is being co-organized by a WSSS PE1 participant to further explore some of the key issues raised at the workshop.

As was noted in the Developing and Suppo rting Software (¬ß4) and the Policy (¬ß5) panel discussions, there are encouraging signs of impro vement, including some altmetric services (such as Impactstory, http://impactstory.org) collectin g metrics for software source code, and the fact that NSF now asks to list ‚Äúproducts‚Äù rather than their ‚Äúp ublications‚Äù in an investigator‚Äôs biosketch or results from prior NSF support.

In addition, there will b e a two-session minisymposium on ‚ÄúReliable Computational Science‚Äù at the 2014 Society for Industrial and Applied Mathematics Annual Meeting (SIAM AN14, http://meetings.siam.org) to f urther explore some of the key issues raised here.
